# Copy this file to .env and fill in values for your project.

# Human-readable project name (used for container name + workdir).
PROJECT_NAME=my-project

# Git repo URL. Use git@ form so the deploy key is used.
REPO_URL=git@github.com:org/repo.git

# Absolute path on THIS machine to the deploy key (private key).
# The key should have commit + pull access to REPO_URL only.
DEPLOY_KEY_PATH=/home/you/.ssh/keys/my-project-deploy

# Port the webapp binds to inside the container.
WEBAPP_PORT=3000

# Coding agents to install in the container (space-separated ids; see the
# registry in container/agents.sh for the full list and package specs). Nothing
# is baked into the base image: every agent listed here is installed at container
# setup, and an agent you omit is genuinely absent. Leave this EMPTY ("") to
# install no agent at all. npm-published agents are installed with
# `pnpm add -g --ignore-scripts` (no package lifecycle scripts run); claude is
# the one exception (`--allow-build`) so its postinstall can place its native
# binary (an npm optionalDependency — still registry-only). Agents not on npm
# (e.g. antigravity) run a vendor installer, which is NOT contained by
# --ignore-scripts.
# Valid ids: claude codex antigravity opencode pi kilocode
# If you add an agent here later, `./launch.sh --update` installs it into the
# running container. Some agents need extra egress hosts — see WHITELIST_HOSTS
# below and container/agents.sh (AGENT_HOSTS); check `egress-log` if one is
# blocked at install/run time.
INSTALL_AGENTS="claude"

# Optional: shell run on every container start, from the repo root, as the
# non-root `dev` user. Use it to spin up a dev server, run migrations, warm
# caches, etc. It's executed as a script, so a multi-line block works (one
# command per line, like WHITELIST_HOSTS). If it blocks (e.g. a foreground
# `pnpm dev`), the container stays alive on it; if it returns, the container
# falls through to a stdin-blocked idle state. To background something, append
# `&` or wrap in `tmux new-session -d -s NAME '...'`. A non-zero exit is logged
# but does not kill the container. If the dev server must be reachable from the
# host, bind to 0.0.0.0 (not 127.0.0.1).
# ON_LAUNCH_SCRIPT="pnpm install && pnpm dev --host 0.0.0.0"
# ON_LAUNCH_SCRIPT="
# pnpm install
# pnpm dev --host 0.0.0.0
# "

# Optional: shell run on every container start, AS ROOT, after the repo is
# cloned and BEFORE ON_LAUNCH_SCRIPT — so it can use repo files and bring up
# services the dev workload depends on. Also a multi-line script. The dev
# workload itself is non-root and `no-new-privileges` blocks sudo, so this is
# the only way to do root-needing launch setup (apt install, starting a system
# service such as clickhouse-server, writing under /etc or /var, etc.). cwd is
# the repo root. A non-zero exit is logged but does not kill the container.
# ON_LAUNCH_ROOT_SCRIPT="
# ./install_clickhouse_local.sh
# clickhouse start --pid-path /var/run/clickhouse-server --config-path /etc/clickhouse-server
# "
# A failing ON_LAUNCH_ROOT_SCRIPT is logged and the launch continues. To stop a
# *hung* one from blocking startup it's run under a timeout (default 600s); the
# dev workload starts regardless. Background long-running services so the script
# returns promptly — the timeout is only a safety net. Override if needed:
# ON_LAUNCH_ROOT_TIMEOUT=600

# Optional: extra ports to publish from the container to the host, beyond
# WEBAPP_PORT. Each entry is either a single port (published as
# host:container on the same number) or "host:container" to remap when the
# host port is busy. All bindings go to 127.0.0.1 only — these are for local
# tools on this machine (DBeaver hitting an in-container ClickHouse, a
# debugger attaching, redis-cli, etc.), not LAN exposure. Whitespace and/or
# newlines separate entries; blanks are ignored.
# EXTRA_PORTS="
# 8123
# 9000
# 16379:6379
# "

# Optional: container resource limits. Defaults: 8g memory, 8 CPUs,
# 16384 pids. Bump PIDS_LIMIT if you plan to run thread-hungry service
# daemons inside (ClickHouse alone asks for 500+ threads at startup).
# MEM_LIMIT=8g
# CPU_LIMIT=8
# PIDS_LIMIT=16384

# Per-project suffix applied to BOTH the image tag and the container name
# (remote-code-<project>-<suffix>), so VS Code Dev Containers keeps each
# project's attach config separate. It caches that config by image name AND by
# container name, so a shared name in either makes it confuse one project's
# container for another's — including the same project running on two hosts.
# create-dev-container.sh generates this randomly and writes it here, so the
# same project bootstrapped on two hosts gets two distinct suffixes. If unset
# (e.g. a hand-written .env), it falls back to a 4-char hash of PROJECT_NAME +
# hostname. Set it explicitly only if you want a fixed value.
# IMAGE_SUFFIX=

# Optional: tmux session name for the `introdus` control plane. On first launch
# `introdus` mints a readable name (introdus-<adjective>-<adjective>-<noun>) and
# writes it here, so the same project always reattaches to the same session. Set
# it explicitly to pin a name. Ignored by the legacy `./launch.sh` flow.
# SESSION_NAME=

# Optional: absolute path on the host to a directory of data the container
# should be able to read. Mounted read-only at /home/dev/shared_data inside the
# container. Leave unset to skip the mount.
# SHARED_DATA_PATH=/home/you/data/my-project-inputs

# Optional: expose the webapp (WEBAPP_PORT) to the public internet via a
# Cloudflare quick tunnel. When true, setup.sh starts `cloudflared` in a
# tmux session and prints the public https://*.trycloudflare.com URL in
# the banner. The URL is stable for the container's lifetime and rotates
# on relaunch. No Cloudflare account required.
#
# IMPORTANT — what you're opting into:
#   - The URL is the only access control. Anyone with it can reach the
#     webapp. Treat it like a secret; don't paste in public channels.
#   - Traffic flows through Cloudflare's edge: they terminate TLS and
#     re-encrypt over the tunnel, so they can see request contents.
#   - Any vulnerability in the webapp is now exposed to the open internet
#     instead of just localhost.
#   - Dev frameworks reject requests where Host isn't localhost. You MUST
#     allow the trycloudflare hostname in your dev server config — e.g.
#     for Vite, add `allowedHosts: ['.trycloudflare.com']` to server in
#     vite.config.js (leading dot = wildcard subdomain). Without this
#     you'll get "Blocked request" pages instead of your app.
#   - Enabling this auto-adds api.trycloudflare.com to the proxy allowlist and
#     allows a pinned set of Cloudflare argotunnel edge IPs directly (by IP, on
#     7844) in the in-container nft filter — cloudflared's edge protocol can't go
#     through the HTTP proxy. See TUNNEL_EDGE_IPS in launch.sh.
# EXPOSE_WEBAPP=true

# Optional: in addition to the local desktop notification, push an alert
# to your phone via https://ntfy.sh whenever the harness fires a
# notification (task complete / awaiting input). ntfy.sh is a free pubsub
# HTTP service: install the ntfy app on your phone, pick a hard-to-guess
# topic name, and subscribe to it. Anyone who knows the topic can publish
# AND read on it, so treat the topic name like a password.
# ENABLE_NOTIFY_SH_ALERTS=true
# NTFY_SH_TOPIC=your-private-topic-7c4a8b9d

# Optional: two-hop remote setup. Set this on a REMOTE host that runs the
# container(s) but has no desktop of its own (e.g. a KVM/VPS box). Instead of
# rendering, host_notify.sh forwards each event over TCP to host:port -- normally
# a loopback port that an SSH reverse tunnel from your laptop carries back to a
# host_listener.py running there, which renders the popup + sound (notification
# titles are tagged with the container's PROJECT_NAME so you can tell them
# apart). This is HOST-LEVEL: a single listener relays every container on this
# host to one laptop, so set it here in the harness .env, not a per-project one.
# On the laptop, install the always-on services once:
#     ./install_dev_machine_listener.sh <ssh-alias-for-this-host> <PORT>
# (PORT must match below). Leave this UNSET on a laptop running containers
# locally. See docs/Running on a remote host.md.
# RC_FORWARD_ADDR=127.0.0.1:8765

# Optional: IP the container's startup self-check dials to prove the egress
# filter is actually dropping non-allowlisted destinations. Must be publicly
# reachable (so its unreachability is due to OUR filter, not a routing
# dead-end) and must NOT be in your allowlist. Defaults to 93.184.216.34.
# CANARY_BLOCKED_IP=93.184.216.34

# Optional: fixed internal targets (DBs, internal registries, etc.) the workload
# may reach DIRECTLY by IP, bypassing the hostname proxy. Whitespace-separated
# IPs/CIDRs. Default empty — the workload reaches the internet only through the
# proxy, for the hostnames below.
# INTERNAL_ALLOW_CIDRS="10.59.0.0/16 10.2.5.131"

# Hostnames the container's egress proxy is allowed to reach (the git host and,
# when EXPOSE_WEBAPP=true, api.trycloudflare.com are added automatically). This
# is a DEFAULT-DENY allowlist enforced by an in-container forward proxy: the
# workload (user `dev`) has NO direct internet egress, so every outbound HTTP(S)
# request is checked here by hostname. A direct dial to a raw IP — even one
# behind an allowlisted name — is dropped, so shared-CDN IPs are not a bypass.
# Each entry matches the host and its subdomains (github.com also matches
# api.github.com). One per line; blank lines and whitespace ignored. Keep it
# tight — only what the project, package managers, and claude actually need.
# (DNS to the container's resolver stays open, so DNS tunnelling is the residual
# exfil channel — a high bar, but real.)
WHITELIST_HOSTS="
github.com
objects.githubusercontent.com
codeload.github.com
raw.githubusercontent.com
api.github.com
registry.npmjs.org
pypi.org
files.pythonhosted.org
api.anthropic.com
claude.ai
platform.claude.com
statsig.anthropic.com
sentry.io
mise.jdx.dev
archive.ubuntu.com
security.ubuntu.com
update.code.visualstudio.com
vscode.download.prss.microsoft.com
marketplace.visualstudio.com
"
